  "local_port": 45252,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What should I do to get selected in GSOC 2018?",
  "response": "Google Summer of Code (GSoC) is a prestigious program that offers students the opportunity to work on open-source projects under the guidance of experienced mentors. While GSoC 2018 has already concluded, the process and strategies for getting selected remain largely consistent across different years. Here's a comprehensive guide to help you understand what it takes to get selected in GSoC, whether for a past year like 2018 or for upcoming editions:\n\n### 1. **Understand What GSoC Is**\nGSoC is a global program that encourages students to participate in open-source development. Selected students receive stipends to work on their proposed projects during the summer, contributing to various open-source organizations.\n\n### 2. **Eligibility Criteria**\nBefore applying, ensure you meet the basic eligibility requirements:\n- **Age:** Must be at least 18 years old at the time of the GSoC program.\n- **Academic Status:** Must be enrolled in an accredited academic institution or have graduated from one within six months of the program's end.\n- **Eligible Countries:** Most countries are eligible, but it's good to check the official [GSoC Eligibility Criteria](https://developers.google.com/open-source/gsoc/faq#who_is_eligible).\n\n### 3. **Choose the Right Organization**\n- **Research Organizations:** Browse the list of participating organizations from previous years on the [GSoC website](https://developers.google.com/open-source/gsoc). Choose one that aligns with your interests and expertise.\n- **Assess Project Ideas:** Look into the project ideas proposed by these organizations. Ensure they excite you and match your skill set.\n- **Community Activity:** Engaging with active and responsive organizations can enhance your chances. Check their communication channels (e.g., mailing lists, forums, chat platforms) and assess their activity levels.\n\n### 4. **Engage Early**\n- **Join Communication Channels:** Participate in forums, mailing lists, or chat groups related to your chosen organization.\n- **Interact with Mentors:** Introduce yourself, ask questions about potential projects, and seek feedback. Building rapport can be advantageous.\n- **Contribute Pre-Application:** Start contributing to the organization's codebase or documentation. Demonstrating your commitment and skills can make your application stand out.\n\n### 5. **Develop a Strong Proposal**\nYour project proposal is crucial. Here\u2019s how to craft one that stands out:\n- **Clear Objectives:** Define what you aim to achieve. Be specific about the features you'll implement or the problems you'll solve.\n- **Detailed Plan:** Break down the project into manageable tasks with timelines. This shows that you've thought through the process.\n- **Feasibility:** Ensure your goals are realistic within the program's duration.\n- **Technical Approach:** Explain the technologies and methods you'll use. Show that you understand the technical requirements.\n- **Past Contributions:** Highlight any previous work with the organization or similar projects. This adds credibility.\n- **Formatting and Clarity:** Present your proposal in a clear, organized manner. Avoid jargon and ensure it's easy to understand.\n\n### 6. **Showcase Your Skills**\n- **Portfolio:** Include links to your GitHub (or other version control platforms) repositories, personal projects, or contributions to open-source.\n- **Relevant Experience:** Detail any previous work or projects that showcase your ability to handle the proposed tasks.\n- **Problem-Solving Ability:** Highlight instances where you've overcome significant challenges in your work.\n\n### 7. **Seek Feedback**\nBefore submitting:\n- **Peer Review:** Have peers or mentors review your proposal for clarity, completeness, and feasibility.\n- **Organization Feedback:** Engage with mentors from the organization to get their input on your proposed project.\n\n### 8. **Submit Before the Deadline**\nEnsure you adhere to the submission deadlines. Late applications are not considered, so plan your timeline accordingly.\n\n### 9. **Prepare for the Selection Process**\n- **Be Responsive:** If the organization reaches out for further information or an interview, respond promptly and professionally.\n- **Stay Engaged:** Continue participating in the community and contributing to projects if possible.\n\n### 10. **Learn from Past Experiences**\nReview successful proposals from previous years to understand what worked. Analyze their structure, content, and how they addressed the project requirements.\n\n### Additional Tips:\n- **Originality:** While it's good to follow certain formats, ensure your proposal is original and reflects your unique approach.\n- **Passion:** Convey your enthusiasm for the project and the organization. Genuine interest can make a significant difference.\n- **Attention to Detail:** Small errors or vague descriptions can detract from an otherwise strong proposal. Proofread thoroughly.\n\n### Resources:\n- **[Official GSoC Guide](https://developers.google.com/open-source/gsoc/resources)**: Comprehensive resources for applicants.\n- **[GSoC Introduction Videos](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLBCF2C3AC7CA1C3B6)**: Visual guides and tips from past participants and mentors.\n- **[Sample Proposals](https://github.com/abhinavmoudgil/GSoC-proposals)**: Examples of successful applications.\n\n### Final Thoughts\nGetting selected for GSoC requires dedication, proactive engagement, and a well-thought-out proposal. Start early, immerse yourself in the open-source community, and showcase your skills and passion effectively. Even though GSoC 2018 has passed, the strategies outlined above remain relevant for future iterations of the program.\n\nGood luck with your GSoC journey!",
